    "note": "Hindi -> English normalization pairs applied (literal substring replace, longest-first) before tokenizing free text for incident-type classification. Shared by src/lib/incidentClassifier.ts (TS, the /api/guess picker UI) and severity_engine/classifier.py (Python, the actual /api/assess dispatch decision) so both understand Hindi consistently -- previously only the TS side had any Hindi support at all, and Python's classifier fell back to an arbitrary placeholder record for every Hindi report.",
    "targetSelection": "English targets are chosen to survive the English stopword filter (generic terms like 'collision'/'vehicle'/'accident'/'road' are deliberately stopworded since they're too common to discriminate between incident types) AND to have real signal in the accident_index.json corpus -- e.g. 'struck' appears 22x in cause/subType text vs 'collided' only 1x, so Hindi collision verbs map to 'struck', not 'collided'. Common noun inflections (oblique plural etc.) are listed as explicit separate entries rather than handled by a stemmer, to avoid over-stripping risk.",
    "order": "Longest Hindi phrase first within each group so multi-word phrases match before a shorter phrase they contain could partially match instead."
